 Mundraumes und der Esslust nach.  aSince the 17th century, palate and taste have been key “technology of the self” used by the new global metropolitan bourgeoisie. The practice of taste, including its communication and staging in a manner divorced from political, economic and bodily needs, holds out the promise of a free and egalitarian society. This history of “mature” taste characterizes a transformation in the realms of orality and appetite.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn German.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 4aEsslust. 4aGeschmack. 4aSinnengeschichte. 4aTischgesellschaft. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aTaste.  aappetite.  ahistory of preferences.  athe dinner party.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus eBook-Package 2019z978311071956708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019z9783110664232oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural and Area Studies 2019z9783110606348oZDB-23-DKU0 cEPUBz97831106383010 cprintz978311063802840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311064034240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110640342423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9783110640342.jpg  a978-3-11-071956-7  DG Plus eBook-Package 2019b2019  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_DGALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA5EBK  aZDB-23-DGGb2019  aZDB-23-DKUb2019